<br>
You should read some of the other threads right now about how some folks co-workers aren't pulling their loads.  Sounds like *more* employers should be keeping an eye on people. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/upickkpockket999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pickk Pockket999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/31/02 11:34:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8023.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Need some help finding Information</span><hr size=1> What you need to remember is that corporate law is written by politicians. Those very politicians that rely on corporate funding to sponsor their campaigns.<br>
<br>
In corporate america the individual has very few rights pertaining to privacy. Now mind you this is not legal advice, but they have the right to monitor your phone calls, read all your emails, watch what you do on your computer and monitor you with video survailence 24/7.<br>
<br>
What they cannot do is monitor you where you have an expectation of privacy. i.e. in the bathroom or a supposed private conference room if you are visiting your lawyer or spiritual advisor etc. Quite frankly if they want to watch every little tiny thing you do with a camera 5 inches from your face they can. If it is really getting to you I would suggest complaining to management that the adverse work conditions are effecting the employees abilities to work effectively and is hurting the bottom line.<br>
<br>
